We can solve this problem by using logarithmic differentiation.

\begin{align*}
\ln(f(x)) &= \ln \left((x^2+1)^7(x^4+2)^5(x^6+3)^3(x^8+4)\right)\\
&= 7 \ln (x^2+1) + 5 \ln (x^4+2) + 3 \ln (x^6+3) + \ln (x^8+4)\end{align*}

Differentiating implicitly yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{f(x)} f'(x)&= \frac{7}{x^2+1}\cdot 2x + \frac{5}{x^4+2}\cdot 4x^3 + \frac{3}{x^6+3}\cdot 6x^5 + \frac{1}{x^8+4} \cdot 8x^7\end{align*}

So

\begin{align*}
f'(x)&= (x^2+1)^7(x^4+2)^5(x^6+3)^3(x^8+4) \left(\frac{14x}{x^2+1} + \frac{20x^3}{x^4+2} + \frac{18x^5}{x^6+3} + \frac{8x^7}{x^8+4} \right)\end{align*}

Alternatively, we could solve this problem ânormally$^{\prime}$ by
using product and chain rule.

\begin{align*}
f'(x)&=7(x^2+1)^6(x^4+2)^5(x^6+3)^3(x^8+4)\cdot2x + 5(x^2+1)^7(x^4+2)^4(x^6+3)^3(x^8+4)\cdot4x^3\\
&\quad + 3(x^2+1)^7(x^4+2)^5(x^6+3)^2(x^8+4)\cdot 6x^5 + (x^2+1)^7(x^4+2)^5(x^6+3)^3\cdot 8x^7\end{align*}

Note that we made use of the general product rule:

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx}(f_1 f_2 f_3 f_4)&= \frac{df_1}{dx} f_2 f_3 f_4 + f_1 \frac{df_2}{dx} f_3 f_4 + f_1 f_2 \frac{df_3}{dx} f_4 + f_1 f_2 f_3 \frac{df_4}{dx}. \end{align*}

which can be found by applying the product rule 3 separate times.
